The secondary-vertex-tagging algorithm, SV1  [38], reconstructs a single displaced secondary vertex in a jet. The reconstruction starts by identifying the possible two-track vertices built with all tracks associated with the jet, while rejecting any tracks making two-track vertices compatible with KS0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$K^{0}_{\text {S}}$$\end{document} or Λ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Lambda $$\end{document} decays, photon conversions or hadronic interactions with the detector material. The SV1 algorithm runs iteratively on all tracks contributing to the selected two-track vertices, trying to fit one secondary vertex. In each iteration, the track-to-vertex matching is evaluated using a χ2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
