				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\chi ^2$$\end{document} is removed and the vertex fit is repeated until an acceptable vertex χ2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\chi ^2$$\end{document} and a vertex invariant mass less than 6 GeV\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\text {GeV}$$\end{document} are obtained. With this approach, the decay products from b- and c-hadrons are typically assigned to a single common secondary vertex. The SV1 algorithm also benefits from several improvements [38] introduced during Run 2, and resulting in increased pile-up rejection and an overall enhancement of the performance at high jet pT\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
