				\begin{document}$$Z'\rightarrow q\bar{q}$$\end{document} events, using TensorFlow [42] with the Keras [42] front-end and the Adam optimiser [43]. The DL1 algorithm, introduced at the beginning of Run 2 in Ref. [6], exploits as input the IP2D, IP3D, SV1 and JetFitter algorithm outputs, while the DL1r algorithm also includes the jet RNNIP output probabilities.

The level of correlation between the different low-level algorithm outputs varies as a function of the jet flavour and the kinematic range. In general, large correlations between the IP2D, IP3D, SV1 and JetFitter algorithms are observed for heavy-flavour jets. However, these correlations are significantly reduced in the case of light-flavour jets. In addition, such correlations are further reduced in high-pT\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p_T$$\end{document} regimes. On the other hand, the RNNIP algorithm contributes a set of input variables which are not strongly correlated. The DL1r algorithm training exploits these correlation differences to reach the best tagging performance.

